body.p:
In typical usage, the sub-regions of the header (the page margin boxes
        @top-left, @top-center, @top-right) and
      footer (@bottom-left, @bottom-center,
        @bottom-right) are distinct regions. If you are specifying content for all
      of them, the content set in one does not use space from the others. Instead, it wraps lines in
      its own region.

body.codeblock:
@page {
      @top-left { content: "A very long publication title..."}
      @top-center { content: "The long organization name..."}
      @top-right { content: counter(page)}
}

@page {
      @top-left { content: "A very long publication title..."}
      @top-right { content:  "The long organization name..." " " counter(page)}
}

body.p:
In the next example, the text in the bottom center will expand to the left and right as
      needed, even if it overlaps the neighbouring page margin boxes, keeping it centered relative
      to the page
      bounds.@page {

    @bottom-center {
        content: "Some text that need to be preserved on a single line and extend left and right.";
        white-space:nowrap;
    }

    @bottom-left {
        content: "Page " counter(page) " of " counter(pages);
        
    }
    @bottom-right {
        content: "Publication title";
    }
}
